Padus, -i, m.: also called the Eridanus, now the Po, the largest river of Italy, flowing from west to east across the whole of the north plain of Cisalpine Gaul. The stream is very violent, and liable to mundations 3 and hence it was for some time regarded as a frontier by the Romans, who planted on its banks the colonies of Cremona and Placentia.
